  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(45) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And sold their possessions and goods.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The verbs throughout this description are in the imperfect tense, as expressing the constant recurrence of the act. The Greek words for “possessions” and “goods” both mean “property,” the former as a thing acquired, the latter as that which belongs to a man for the time being. Custom, however, had introduced a technical distinction, and “possessions” stands for real property, “goods” for personal. So in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the former word is used interchangeably with that which is translated “field,” and in the LXX. of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 23:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 31:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is used both for “field” and “vineyard.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As every man had need.—The words imply at least the endeavour to discriminate. The money was not given literally to every one who applied for it, and so the way was prepared for more fixed and definite rules.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "As every man had need.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The words imply at least the endeavour to discriminate. The money was not given literally to every one who applied for it, and so the way was prepared for more fixed and definite rules.",
