        "text": "] [not ‘every man,’ A.V.] had need”. See Rendall, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Acts, in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 4:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Expositor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", vii., p. 358, 3rd series.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καθότι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": peculiar to St. Luke; in Gospel twice, and in Acts four times, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἄν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " makes the clause more indefinite: it is found in relative clauses after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὅς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὅστις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc., with the indicative—here it is best explained as signifying “accidisse aliquid non certo quodam tempore, sed quotiescumque occasio ita ferret,” quoted by Wendt from Herm., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ad Vig.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 820; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:56",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Blass, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Viteau, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Le Grec du N. T.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 142 (1893). Grimm renders ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καθότι ἄν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " here “in so far,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "or",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " “so often as,” “according as”. Spitta refers ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:45-47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to the Apostles only, but to justify this he is obliged to refer ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to his reviser. Hilgenfeld brackets the whole verse, referring it to his “author to Theophilus,” retaining ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", whilst Weiss also refers the whole verse to a reviser, who introduced it in imitation of St. Luke’s love of poverty as indicated in his Gospel. But by such expedients the picture of the whole body of the believers sharing in the Apostles’ life and liberality is completely marred.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "45",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And sold their possessions",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.] For the money which resulted from such sales would be the most convenient form in which their bounty could be bestowed on those who needed it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as every man had need",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "according as any man had need",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We gather from this that the first converts kept their homes and things needful for themselves, but held the rest as a trust for the Church to be bestowed whenever need was seen. This is an earlier stage than that in which the money was brought and put at the disposal of the Apostles.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
